04208nam a22005775i 9780773558052DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735580527 a10.1515/97807735580522doi  a(DE-B1597)657574  a(OCoLC)1083125904  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aTR61b.L44 2019 7aPHO0231002bisacsh04a770.941109/0342231 aLee, Anthony W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Global Flows of Early Scottish Photography :bEncounters in Scotland, Canada, and China /cAnthony W. Lee. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b193 photos, full colour throughout  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Beaverbrook Canadian Foundation Studies in Art History ;v2600tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTitles, Dates, and Transliterations -- tIntroduction -- tAt the Shoreline of the Fisherfolk -- tA Wilderness of one's Own -- tUpriver and Down -- tConclusion -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlmost immediately after the invention of photography, Scottish photographers took their clunky cameras on the road to capture the stories of peoples and communities touched by the forces of British imperialism. For the next thirty years, their journeys would take them far from their homes in the Lowlands to the Canadian wilderness and the treaty ports and rivers of China. The Global Flows of Early Scottish Photography is about the interplay between these photographers' ambitions and the needs and desires of the people they met. Anthony Lee tracks the work of several famous innovators of the art form, including the pioneering team of D.O. Hill and Robert Adamson in Edinburgh; Canada's first great photographers, the Scottish immigrants William Notman and Alexander Henderson in Montreal; the globetrotting John Thomson in Hong Kong; and Lai Afong, the first widely known Chinese photographer. Lee reveals their pictures in the context of migration and the social impact wrought by worldwide trade and competing nationalisms. A timely book, it tells of an era when cameras emerged to give shape and meaning to some of the most defining moments brought about by globalization in the nineteenth century. Beautifully written and richly illustrated in full colour, The Global Flows of Early Scottish Photography weaves stories together to show that even the earliest pictures were sites of fierce historical struggle.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGlobalizationxHistoryy19th century. 0aPhotographerszScotlandxHistoryy19th century. 0aPhotographyxHistoryy19th century. 0aPhotographyxTechniquexHistoryy19th century. 0aPhotographyzScotlandxHistoryy19th century. 7aPhotography / Subjects & Themes / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355805240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773558052423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773558052/original  a978-3-11-127268-9  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-127498-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019b2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles